    <prp:abstract>MS0451.6-0305 is a unique system, consisting of a compact group of star-forming 
galaxies at z=2.9 being strongly lensed by a rich galaxy cluster at z=0.55.  
Images of the field are dramatically different across wavebands, with a 
giant arc seen at around 1mm, while HST helps us to identify 7 multiply-imaged 
galaxies, representing perhaps the most complex lensing system known.  A novel 
modelling technique, combining source positions and SEDs, has enabled us to 
distinguish 4 main contributors to the submm emission detected by SCUBA, 
SCUBA-2, AzTEC and Herschel.  ALMA's dramatically smaller effective beamsize 
will provide the definitive test of our predictions.  Because of the lensing, 
the new observations will probe the physical conditions in a high-z group of 
interacting galaxies at greatly magnified brightness levels and spatial 
resolution.  Additionally, as an extreme case of extended and morphologically 
complex star-formation, this z=2.9 group can act as a test-bed for the 
simplified modelling usually carried out for strong lensing systems at 
these wavelengths.</prp:abstract>
